    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Is Smoking Just About Choice?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lois Taylor letter on Mario Vargas Llosa's Sept 1 article holds smokers should pay for own health care</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Languid Sort of Suicide,'' by  Mario Vargas Llosa (Op-Ed, Sept. 1):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Languid Sort of Suicide,'' by  Mario Vargas Llosa (Op-Ed, Sept. 1):</p>
        <p>I agree that for the government to prohibit smoking would be an undesirable encroachment on individual liberty. But there is one aspect of the problem that Mr. Vargas Llosa does not mention: the huge sums of public money spent to maintain those suffering from smoking-related illness.  Whether or not to smoke is a conscious decision, made in the light of an abundance of information on the lethal effects of tobacco. Surely those who choose unwisely should bear the cost of any resulting ill health.</p>
        <p>LOIS TAYLOR  Old Greenwich, Conn., Sept. 1, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
